Here is the R code to generate synthetic data for laser-accelerated ion beams:

```R
# Define the parameters
target_material <- c("plastic", "aluminium", "polypropylene", "polystyrene")
target_thickness <- runif(25, 0.1, 10)
pulse_width <- runif(25, 30, 12900)
energy <- runif(25, 0.3, 1000)
spot_size <- runif(25, 2.13, 60)
intensity <- runif(25, 1.05e18, 5.59e21)
power <- runif(25, 1.76e11, 3.83e14)
cutoff_energy <- runif(25, 3.3, 95)

# Reverse the process to generate new data points
new_data <- array()
for(i in 1:25) {
  # Determine the intensity and power based on cutoff energy
  intenisty <- (4.07e2 * cutoff_energy^(0.672)) + 6.22e20
  power <- (4.07e15 * cutoff_energy^(0.584)) + 7.68e13
  
  # Decide on spot size, energy, and pulse width based on intensity and power
  spot_size <- (1.16e2 * intensity^(0.646) / power^(0.584))
  energy <- (4.98e1 * target_thickness^(0.250) + 2.35)
  pulse_width <- (1.69e4 * energy^(0.343) + 30)
  
  # Choose appropriate target thickness and target material
  target_thickness <- ifelse(cutoff_energy < 8, runif(1, 0.1, 10), runif(1, 6, 12))
  target_material <- sample(target_material, 1)[[1]]
  
  new_data[i, ] <- c(target_material, target_thickness, pulse_width, energy, spot_size, intenisty, power, cutoff_energy)
}

new_data
```

The output will be an array of 25 samples with the following features: `target_material`, `target_thickness`, `pulse_width`, `energy`, `spot_size`, `intensity`, `power`, and `cutoff_energy`.
